data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Instead, you use **constructor/`IDisposable`** for per-test setup/teardown, and **`IClassFixture<T>`** for one-time class-level setup/teardown.

Here's the converted class:

```csharp
// One-time setup/teardown → shared fixture class
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // [OneTimeSetUp]
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // [OneTimeTearDown]
    }
}

// [TestFixture] → no attribute needed; use IClassFixture<T> + IDisposable
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor = [SetUp] (runs before each test)
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Dispose = [TearDown] (runs after each test)
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]  // [Test] → [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a fixture class |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` | `Assert.NotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.EqualTo(y))` | `Assert.Equal(y, x)` |

Note: xUnit creates a **new instance** of the test class per test, so the constructor/Dispose naturally give you per-test isolation. The fixture class is instantiated once and shared via dependency injection through the constructor parameter.
